  </properties>
  <body>
    <section name="SchemaCrawler - Database-Specific Queries Example">
      <subsection name="Description">
        <p>SchemaCrawler has the capability to execute any arbitrary SQL,
          even if
          the SQL is
          database-specific. This example demonstrates how
          to execute
          arbitrary SQL.
        </p>
      </subsection>
      <subsection name="How to Run">
        <ol>
          <li>
            Make sure that
            <span class="code">java</span>
            is on your
            <span class="code">PATH</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            Start the database server by running the
            <span class="code">StartDatabaseServer</span>
            script from the
            distribution directory
          </li>
          <li>
            Start a command shell in the
            <span class="code">db-specific-query</span>
            example directory.
          </li>
          <li>
            Run
            <span class="code">db-specific-query.cmd</span>
            (or
            <span class="code">db-specific-query.sh</span>
            on
            Unix).
          </li>
        </ol>
      </subsection>
      <subsection name="How to Experiment">
        <ol>
          <li>
            Try generating different output formats, such as HTML or JSON.
          </li>
          <li>
            Try modifying the
            <span class="code">schemacrawler.config.properties</span>
            with
            different queries.
          </li>
          <li>
            Redirect the output of SchemaCrawler into a file, by running
            <span class="code">db-specific-query.cmd &gt; file.txt</span>
            .
          </li>
        </ol>
      </subsection>
    </section>
  </body>
